@NODE Installation "Installation"


 @{B}Installation@{UB}

 Copy 'citra.lib' and citra_gcc.lib to 'StormC:Libs' and the 'citra' directory
 to 'StormC:Include'.

 You may choose other destinations but then you have to edit the demo project
 files.

 citra.lib is for StormC v3 and is compiled for 68000 with Near Data (A4) Model.

 citra_gcc.lib is for GCC and is compiled for 68000 with Far Data Model.

 To compile the Demo you may have to remove two lines in 'gadgets/layout.h'
 (they causes a redefinition error!).


@ENDNODE

@NODE Description "Description"

 @{B}Overall description@{UB}

 An Amiga OS "objects" (a device, a port, a visible object etc.) is implemented as
 a C++ class. Some examples:

         object     |     class
     ---------------+--------------
         screen     |   CITScreen
     ---------------+--------------
         window     |   CITWindow
     ---------------+--------------
      button gadget |   CITButton
     ---------------+--------------
         timer      |    CITimer
     ---------------+--------------

 The classes have constructors to initialize the object and to set default values
 for the attributes and they have methods to set the attributes to aother values.

 Let's have a look at the example program from the @{"Introduction" LINK Introduction}

 010 #include <citra/CITGroup.h>
 020 #include <citra/CITButton.h>
 030 #include <citra/CITPalette.h>
 040
 050 CITApp Application;
 060
 070 CITWorkbench DemoScreen;
 080 CITWindow    DemoWindow;
 090 CITVGroup    winGroup;
 100 CITPalette   palette;
 110 CITButton    quitButton;
 120
 130 void CloseEvent() { Application.Stop(); }
 140 void QuitEvent(ULONG ID,ULONG eventFlag) { Application.Stop(); }
 150
 160 int main()
 170 {
 180   BOOL Error=FALSE;
 190
 200   // Build GUI
 210   //
 220   DemoScreen.InsObject(DemoWindow,Error);
 230     DemoWindow.CloseGadget();
 240     DemoWindow.SizeGadget();
 250     DemoWindow.DepthGadget();
 260     DemoWindow.Caption("CITPalette Demo");
 270     DemoWindow.CloseEventHandler(CloseEvent);
 280     DemoWindow.InsObject(winGroup,Error);
 290       winGroup.SpaceOuter();
 300       winGroup.InsObject(palette,Error);
 310         palette.MinWidth(200);
 320         palette.MinHeight(150);
 330         palette.NumColours(256);
 340       winGroup.InsObject(quitButton,Error);
 350         quitButton.Text("Quit");
 360         quitButton.MaxHeight(20);
 370         quitButton.EventHandler(QuitEvent);
 380
 390   // Put the screen into Application to create the GUI and set up
 400   // the event system
 410   //
 420   Application.InsObject(DemoScreen,Error);
 430
 440   if( Error ) return 10;
 450
 460   Application.Run(); // Will return when Quit or close gadget is pressed
 470
 480   return 0;
 490 }

 In the lines 070-110 variables for the object used in the program are declared
 (resulting in the constructors for to be called). In line 220 the window is
 inserted in the screen. The window will not open since the screen is not yet
 put into the Application.

 In lines 230-250 attributes for the window are set. In the next line we are
 telling the window object that the routine in line 130 should be called when
 the close gadget are pressed.

 In the following lines a vertical group is inserted in the vindow and two gadgets
 are inserted in this group. Note that also the quitButton has been informed
 to call a routine when the button is pressed.

 Now the whole GUI is build and by inserting the screen in the Application
 every thing opens.

 If there is no errors the Run method in the Application is called (line 460).
 This method waits for signals to arrive then it calls event handlers in the
 objects that has asked for this signal. This object in turn calls our routines
 (line 130 and 140). Having called these handlers it checks to se if the Stop
 method has been called. If this is the case it returns. Otherwise it loops back
 to wait for a signal to arrive.

 In line 480 the program ends. C++ will clean up by calling the destructors.
 Some times it is wise to clean up your self before returning. This is done
 by executing the statement:

   Application.RemObject(DemoScreen);


