@NODE Application "Application"

 @{B}Application@{UB}

 CITApp is the main class. There must be exactly one instance of this class in
 a program. Typically there is a declaration of the form

   CITApp Application;

 in the main module.

 CITApp handles the whole event/exception system.


 @{B}Super Class@{UB}

   none


 @{B}Public Methods@{UB}

   void InsObject(CITAppClass& Object,BOOL& Err)

     Insert an object of type @{I}CITAppClass@{UI} (for instance @{"CITTimer" LINK Timer} or @{"CITScreen" LINK Screen}) in
     the Application object. Object will be put into the event system.

     Before the call the parameter Err must be TRUE (@{I}InsObject@{UI} will return without
     doing anything) or FALSE and at return the value of Err will be TRUE if Object
     could not be inserted.

   void RemObject(CITAppClass& Object)

     Remove an object inserted by @{I}InsObject@{UI}.


   ULONG Run(ULONG stopMask)
   void  Stop(ULONG stopMask)

     A call to the @{I}Run@{UI} routine will start the event system. It will return as soon
     as one (or more) of the bits in the parameter @{I}stopMask@{UI} has been set by a call
     to the @{I}Stop@{UI} routine.

     The default parameter for these methods is MAIN_STOPMASK.

     To better understand how it works here is the code for @{I}Run@{UI} and @{I}Stop@{UI}:

       ULONG CITApp::Run(ULONG stopMask)
       {
         ULONG retMask;

         while( (retMask = stopReq & stopMask) == 0 )
           HandleEvent( Wait(WaitSignal) );

         stopMask &= ~MAIN_STOPMASK;
         stopReq  &= ~stopMask;

         return retMask;;
       }

       void CITApp::Stop(ULONG stopMask)
       {
         stopReq |= stopMask;
       }

     It's legal to call Run from an event routine.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Timer "Timer"

 @{B}Timer@{UB}

 CITTimer  handles timer events/exceptions.

 @{B}Super Class@{UB}

   CITAppClass (see @{"CITApp" LINK Application})


 @{B}Public Methods@{UB}

  void AddEvent(double t,void (*p)(),BYTE prior);

    The event routine @{I}void p()@{UI} will be called after @{I}t@{UI} secs.

    If @{I}prior@{UI} is 0 it will be called as a normal event routine. If @{I}prior@{UI} is 1
    it will be called as a task exception. You need to program the event routine
    much more carefully in this case!

    Task exception is not implementet in GCC versions. The parameter priority
    is simply ignored.

    The default parameter for @{I}prior@{UI} is 0.

    Example: Set the timer to call the event routine regularily with intervals
      of 1 second:

            :
            :

          Application.InsObject(timer,Error);

            :

          timer.AddEvent(1.0,timerEvent);

          Application.Run();


            :

        void timerEvent()
        {
            :

          timer.AddEvent(1.0,timerEvent);
        }


  void AddEvent(double t,void* obj,void (*p)(void* obj),BYTE prior);

    The same as above but used if the event routine is a member function for
    some class (see @{"CITWindow" LINK Window} for more information).

  void Abort(void (*p)());
  void Abort(void* obj,void (*p)(void* obj));

    Abort the timer event started by @{I}AddEvent@{UI}.


  The Timer module also offers three timer functions:

    void SysTime(ULONG& t)
    void SysTime(double& t)

      Read the system time.

    ULONG EClock(struct EClockVal& ev)

      Read the EClock.

@ENDNODE

