      An image to render.  Any number of images can be provided in a label.


   void DisposeImage(BOOL b)

      If parameter is TRUE it indicates that you want the current image (image
      passed as parameter in method @{I}Image@{UI} before this call) to be disposed
      automatically when the label instance is disposed.

      Default parameter is TRUE.

      Default value is FALSE.

   void Mapping(UWORD* map,DrawInfo* drInfo)

      The parameter @{I}map@{UI} is a pen mapping array affecting the current image
      (image passed as parameter in method @{I}Image@{UI} before this call).

      The mapping array must have at least as many elements as the image has bit
      planes (i.e. 1 << Image.Depth).  For element i in the array you put in the
      new pen that you want pen i in your image to be mapped to. For a typical
      4-colour image, you  might use the following mapping:

      If there is a default DrawInfo (if it is connected to a screen) or if the
      parameter @{I}drInfo@{UI} is non NULL your mapping values will be changed in
      the following way:

        mapping[0] = drInfo->dri_Pens[map[0]];
        mapping[1] = drInfo->dri_Pens[map[1]];
        mapping[2] = drInfo->dri_Pens[map[2]];
        mapping[3] = drInfo->dri_Pens[map[3]];

          :

      This new map wil be used as data value for the Reaction attribute LABEL_Mapping.

      Default @{I}drInfo@{UI} parameter is NULL.


   void Justification(UWORD pos)

      Justification for entire label.  This can be either LJ_LEFT (the default),
      LJ_CENTRE or LJ_RIGHT.


 @{B}Example:@{UB}

        :

   UWORD map[] = {BACKGROUNDPEN,SHADOWPEN};

        :

      label.Justification(LABEL_CENTRE);
      label.Text("_Under-scored\\nNot under-scored\\n");
      label.Text("An image:");
      label.Image(&image);
        label.Mapping(map);
      label.Text("\\nChange fonts,\\n");
        label.FGPen(3);
        label.Font("emerald.font",18);
      label.Text("and colours,");
        label.FGPen(2);
      label.Text(" and styles");
        label.SoftStyle(FSF_BOLD);


